	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I believe that good game design may not necessarily have exact guidelines, but rather it just has to work and be fun. Since I've been playing games my whole life I personally feel as if I have a somewhat of a video game &quot;intuition&quot; so to speak. <br /><br />If someone makes a game and I play test it and feel that something isn't just quite right I make a suggestion to change it. If I make something myself and play it and just don't think its fun I try and change it as well. <br /><br />I believe that if I'm not having fun playing something then other people aren't as well. Here is one example of something I suggested to my good friend who is working on a Link to the Past hack. <br /><br />Here was the original overworld screen by Seph<br /><br /><img src="http://i48.photobucket.com/albums/f246/finaltheorygames/sephhhhhh_zpsui8xvki7.png" alt="Image" /><br /><br />and here is my modified version. <br /><br /><img src="http://i48.photobucket.com/albums/f246/finaltheorygames/mine%20change%20seph_zps8xy8so8p.png" alt="Image" /><br /><br />Would you agree with my design changes?<br /><br />I deleted a barrier in the middle because I felt that it was too cramped and fixed a perspective error on the far right high level hill. <br /><br />Here is a link of a preview of the game. Its by the same person as Parallel Worlds hack. <br /><br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ONgjEp4YOg4">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ONgjEp4YOg4</a><!-- m -->

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


